The Cox RFX model

Preliminaries

set.seed(42)

A random effects model

To estimate survival we use an extension of the Cox proportional hazards model. In this model the hazard, given a set of covariates \(Z\) is expressed as \[\lambda = \lambda_0(t) \exp(Z u) \] where \(u\) denotes the risk coefficients.The random effects model assumes that the coefficients \(u_j\) are from a shared distribution \[u_j \sim N(\mu, \sigma^2).\] This assumption make the model a hierarchical model, which is often referred to as a random effects model. The assumption of a shared distribution with a finite variance effectively regularises the model and allows for estimating parameters even in high-dimensional cases.

A second idea of our model is that our the set of covariates \(Z = (Z_1,…,Z_g)\) can be split into \(g\) groups, each with a different distribution of effect sizes, \[ u_j \sim N(\mu_g(j), \sigma^2_g(j))\].

The means \(\mu_g\) can be estimated utilising the decomposition of the log-hazard, \(h_i = \sum_g h_{ig}\), \(h_{ig} = \sum_{j\in g} X_{ij}u_j = \sum_{j\in g} X_{ij}(u_j - \mu_g) + \sum_{j\in g} X_{ij}\mu\). So one can estimate each \(\mu_g\) as the coefficient of the introducing auxillary variables \(\bar X_g = \sum_{j\in g} X_{ij}\), which are simply the row-wise sums of the covariates of each group.

To estimate the centred parameters \(u'_j = u_j - \mu_{g(j)}\), we exploit that the constraint induced by the normal prior distributions is equivalent to a ridge penalty. This gives the MAP estimates \[u_j^* \mid \sigma_g(j)^2, Z = u_j^{ridge},\] which are implemented in R using the ridge() function in coxph().

To estimate the variances \(\sigma_g^2\) we can then iterate between the MAP estimates \(u^*\) and \[\sigma_g^2 \mid u_j^*,j\in g = \frac{\sum_ju_j^2 }{df} \] where \(df\) are the effective degrees of freedom, \(df = \mathrm{tr} [(H_{gg}+\sigma_g^2 I)(H_{gg})^{-1}]\), \(H\) being the Hessian of the total likelihood, evaluated for elements of group \(g\).

The covariance of the coefficients \(u_j = u_j' + \mu_{g(j)}\) can be derived from the \((p+|g|) \times (p+|g|)\) covariance matrix \(V\) of the coeffient vector \((u', \mu)\), \(\Sigma_u = B^T V B\), where \(B = (\mathbb{1}_p, I(j\in g)\) maps \((u', \mu)\) to \(u\). There exist two different estimates of \(V\), either \(V=H^{-1}\) or \(V = H^{-1} \mathcal{I} H^{-1}\), but we find that the former tends to be overly conservative.

Optionally one may define a hyperprior for \(\sigma^2_g \sim \operatorname{si}\chi^2(\nu, \sigma_0^2)\), which can help stabilize the estimates.

The implementation of the model is straightforward:

Variance components

The variance of the log hazard \(h = Z u\) can be written as \[ \begin{aligned} Var[h] &= E[Var[h|u]] + Var[E[h|u]] \cr &= E_u Var_Z [Zu] + Var_u[E[Z]u] \cr &\approx \hat u^T \Sigma_X \hat u + E[Z]^T \Sigma_u E[Z]\cr &= V + E[\sigma^2_0]. \end{aligned} \] The interpretation of the two terms are the following: The first is the predicted variance \(V\) using fixed parameters \(\hat u\) stemming from the variance in the covariates. The second term is the uncertainty of the prediction resulting from the variance in the coefficient estimates. It is tempting to approximate the moments of \(u\) with the estimates from the fit. The covariance \(\Sigma_Z\) can be estimated across the rows of \(Z\). The covariance of \(u\) can be estimated in the fitting process. \[ \begin{aligned} Var[h] & \approx Var_Z [Z^T \hat u] + E[Z \hat\Sigma_u Z] \cr &= \hat u^T \Sigma_Z \hat u + E[Z^T \hat\Sigma_u Z] \end{aligned} \] The explained variance \(V\) involves summations over all terms \(j\) of \(Z_ij\). These can be partitioned into groups g, \[ \begin{aligned} V &= \sum_j \sum_k u_j u_k {\Sigma_Z}_{jk} \cr &= \sum_g \sum_h V{gh}, \end{aligned} \] where \(V{gh} = \sum_{j \in g}\sum_{k \in h} u_j u_k ({\Sigma_Z})_{jk}\). \(V_{gh}\) is the covariance matrix of the risk contributions. Ignoring off-diagonal terms in \(V_{gh}\) the risk can hence be written as \[ Var[h] \approx \sum_g V_{gg} + E[\sigma^2_0].\] The actual implementation is straightforward:

comp <- lapply(1:10, function(i){
            surv <-  CoxHD:::SimSurv(risk = risk)
            fit <-  CoxRFX(Z, surv, groups = groups, sigma0 = 0.1, nu=0)
            riskComponents <- sapply(levels(groups), function(g)  Z[,groups==g] %*% a[groups==g])
            varComp <- VarianceComponents(fit)
            c(varComp, Residual=mean((predict(fit) - risk)^2))
        })

Comparison to frailty models

For a factorial set of covariates (i.e., \(Z_{ij} \in \{0,1\}; \sum_j Z_{i,j}=1 \forall i\)), the model is equivalent to a frailty model

set.seed(42)
par(mfrow=c(3,3))
for(nLevels in c(5,10,50))
    for(n in c(2,10,50)){
        f <- factor(rep(1:nLevels, each=n))
        Z1 <- sapply(1:nLevels, `==`, f) +0
        b <- rnorm(nLevels)
        r <- Z1 %*% b
        s <- CoxHD:::SimSurv(r)
        frailtyFit <- coxph(s ~ frailty(f, "gaussian"))
        rfxFit <- CoxRFX(Z1, s, sigma0=1, which.mu=NULL)
        if(nLevels<=5)
            y <- frailtyFit$coef
        else
            y <- frailtyFit$frail
        plot(coef(rfxFit), y, xlab='CoxRFX est', ylab="Frailty est", pch=19, xlim=range(coef(rfxFit)), ylim=range(coef(rfxFit)))
        title(main=paste(nLevels, "levels,", n,"obs"))
        points(coef(rfxFit), b, pch=1)
        abline(0,1)
    }

Missing data

If we a proportion missing data \(X_m\) and observed data \(X_o\), we can impute predictions using the correlation structure \(\Sigma_X\) of the training data set. Under normality assumptions one can use the covariance matrix from the training data to obtain the conditional (posterior) distribution of the missing data: \[ \begin{aligned} X_m | X_o & \sim N(\mu_m^*, \Sigma_m^*) \cr \mu_m^* &= \mu_m + \Sigma_{mo} \Sigma_{oo}^{-1} (X_o - \mu_o) \cr \Sigma_m^* &= \Sigma_{mm} - \Sigma_{mo} \Sigma_{oo}^{-1} \Sigma_{om}. \end{aligned} \]

As the risk predictions are linear in \(X\) the distribution of the prediction error is given by \[ \begin{aligned} E[\lambda | X_o, u] &= X_o u_o + \mu_m^* u_m \cr Var[\lambda | X_o, u ] &= u_m^T \Sigma_m^* u_m \end{aligned} \] The uncertainty in \(u\) introduces a second term \[ Var[\lambda | X_o] = Var[\lambda | X_o, u ] + (X_o - \mu_o, \mu_m^* - \mu_m)^T \Sigma_u (X_o -\mu_o, \mu^*_m -\mu_m). \] The implementation is

If nothing is missing this is equivalent to the standard variance estimates of the glm predictors \(\sigma^2_i = X_ij {\Sigma_u}_{jk} X_ik\):

plot(PredictRiskMissing(fit, var="var")[,2], predict(fit, se.fit=TRUE)$se.fit^2, xlab = "sigma^2 CoxHD", ylab="sigma^2 coxph")


for(m in c(0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.5, 0.75, 0.9, 0.95)){
    par(bty="L", mfrow=c(1,2))
    nNewZ <- 500
    newZ <- fit$Z[1:nNewZ,]
    newZ[sample(1:length(newZ),length(newZ) * m, replace = FALSE)] <- NA
    p <- PredictRiskMissing(fit, newZ[1:nNewZ,])
    p0 <- risk[1:nNewZ]
    plot(p0[1:100], p[1:100,1], xlab="True risk", ylab= "Predicted risk", main=paste(100*m,"% missing", sep=""), ylim=range(p0), xlim=range(p0))
    segments(p0[1:100], p[1:100,1] - 2*sqrt(p[1:100,2]),p0[1:100], p[1:100,1] + 2*sqrt(p[1:100,2]), col="#88888844", lwd=4 )
    abline(0,1)
    legend("topleft", bty="n", c(paste("Cor =", round(cor(p[,1],p0),2), collapse=""), paste("RSS =", round(mean((p0 - p[,1])^2), 2), collapse=""), paste("^RSS =", round(mean(p[,2]), 2), collapse="") ))
    plot(survfit(surv[1:nNewZ] ~ (p[,1] >  median(p[,1]))), xlab="Time", ylab="Survival")
    legend("topright", bty="n",paste("C = ", round(rcorr.cens(-p[,1], surv[1:nNewZ])[1],2), collapse=""))
}


library(Matrix)
for(rho in -4:-1){
    m <- 0.75
    par(bty="L", mfrow=c(1,3))
    Z <- rmvnorm(nObs, mean=rep(0,nParam), sigma = diag(beta) + as.matrix(bdiag(lapply(1:nGroups, function(i) matrix(10^rho, nrow=nParam/nGroups, ncol=nParam/nGroups)))))
    Z[] <- Z > quantile(Z, 0.75)
    risk = Z %*% a
    risk <- risk / sd(risk)
    s <- CoxHD:::SimSurv(risk)
    fit <- CoxRFX(Z, s, groups=groups)
    nNewZ <- 500
    newZ <- fit$Z[1:nNewZ,]
    newZ[sample(1:length(newZ),length(newZ) * m, replace = FALSE)] <- NA
    p <- PredictRiskMissing(fit, newZ[1:nNewZ,], var="var2")
    p0 <- risk[1:nNewZ]
    plot(p0[1:100], p[1:100,1], xlab="True risk", ylab= "Predicted risk", main=paste(100*m,"% missing, rho=", 10^rho, sep=""), ylim=range(p0), xlim=range(p0))
    segments(p0[1:100], p[1:100,1] - 2*sqrt(p[1:100,2]),p0[1:100], p[1:100,1] + 2*sqrt(p[1:100,2]), col="#88888844", lwd=4 )
    abline(0,1)
    legend("topleft", bty="n", c(paste("Cor =", round(cor(p[,1],p0),2), collapse=""), paste("RSS =", round(mean((p0 - p[,1])^2), 2), collapse=""), paste("^RSS =", round(mean(p[,2]), 2), collapse="") ))
    plot(a/sd( Z %*% a), fit$coefficients, xlab="True coef", ylab="Est. coef")
    abline(0,1)
    plot(survfit(s[1:nNewZ] ~ (p[,1] >  median(p[,1]))), xlab="Time", ylab="Survival")
    legend("topright", bty="n",paste("C = ", round(rcorr.cens(-p[,1], s[1:nNewZ])[1],2), collapse=""))
}
